Muhammad, Hell And Allah's Mercy


    Isn't one of the religious impulses so that we avoid hellfire? In our opinion, no believer wants to be punished by Allah. It is known! Who wants to fall into the hands of the ‚ÄúRuler of the Day of Judgment?‚Äù Thus the Scriptures show the way to avoid hellfire and find God's Mercy.

    The following is the view of the Holy Book of Allah and the prophet of Islam regarding hell and Allah's mercy.

    Hell And Allah's Mercy, According To The Koran And Muhammad

    Many Muslims often ask, "where is the verse that Muhammad is not sure he will go to heaven or Muhammad does not know whether he will go to heaven or hell, please show me?" We try to share what the Quran and hadith convey as representatives of the prophet of Islam.

    Because of the understanding and questions above, the writings in the Qur'an and the Hadith of Bukhari confuse us. For example, according to the Muslim prophet, it is certain that all Muslims will go to hell (Surah 19:71). Because nothing can help them escape that hell.

    Muhammad did not know whether he was going to heaven or hell. Even the prophet of Islam himself admitted that he could not help his family and nation from Allah's torment. This is narrated by Hadith Bukhari.
    From Abu Huraira r.a. he said: "The Messenger of Allah. Standing when God the Most Noble and Most Great revealed a verse which means: "And warn your closest relatives!" Then he said: "O people of Quresy! (or a word similar to it). Redeem yourself! I can't help you anything from the torment of God. Hi Bani Abdi Manaf! I can't help you one bit. Hi Abbas son of Abdul Mutholib! I can't help you one bit from God's torment. ‚ÄúO Safiah, aunt of the Messenger of Allah! I can't help you one bit from God's torment. Hi Fatimah bint Muhammad! Ask me for wealth and I can't help you one bit from God's torment!‚Äù (Hadith Shohih Bukhari Volume 4, number 16).

    Muhammad Wants to Avoid Hell and Needs Allah's Grace

    We do not want to guess whether Muhammad went to hell or heaven, as well as the fate of Muslims. However, according to Muhammad it is not only Muslims, their families and nations that cannot be saved. Not even himself could be saved. This is also narrated by Abu Hurairah: "From the Messenger of Allah. that he said: None of you will be saved by his deeds. A man asked: Neither do you, O Messenger of Allah? Rasulullah saw. replied: Neither do I , it's just that Allah has bestowed His mercy on me but you still try to do and say the right thing‚Äù (Hadith Shohih Bukhari Volume 8, number 470).

    One of the Purposes of Sholawat is "Praying Muhammad Not to Go to Hell"
    Therefore, Muhammad asked his people to pray for him, so that he would get the "mercy" of Allah (Qs 33:56). And also Muhammad taught that his people do not despair of asking Allah to get Allah's mercy for themselves (Surah 39:53).

    This means that religion and charity do not guarantee entry to heaven. The only way out for Muslims to escape from hell is only to receive and receive God's grace.

    Isa Al-Masih and the Mercy of Allah

    When Maryam asked the angel Gabriel about who she was carrying, Gabriel replied: ‚ÄúThus, your Lord said: 'That is easy for Me; and that We may make it a sign for mankind and as a mercy from Us. . .'‚Äù (Surah 19:21).

    In other words, Isa Al-Masih is grace itself. This grace has been promised by God to the prophets and is eagerly awaited by all the people. The coming of Jesus Christ to the world means that God's promise will be fulfilled (Gospel, Apostle Luke 1:72; 4:19).

    Isa Al-Masih Guarantees Eternal Life for His Followers

    As for the purpose of this Grace coming, that man might be saved: ‚ÄúBut God, being rich in mercy, because of the great love he had for us, made us alive together with Christ, even though we were dead in our trespasses. us‚Äìby grace you are saved‚Äù (Gospel, Ephesians 2:4-5).
    Hell and God's Grace, of course everyone will choose to avoid hell and receive God's Grace. Grace can only be obtained through Isa Al-Masih. He is the Grace of God who has come and will come on the Day of Judgment to give eternal life to those who believe (Gospel, Letter of the Great Apostle Jude 21).

    Isa Al-Masih himself promised his followers, namely those who are truly saved (more than Christian descendants), ‚ÄúI give them eternal life, and they will never perish, and no one will snatch them from their hands. me‚Äù (Gospel, Great Apostle John 10:28). How beautiful is this promise of eternal life that is given to everyone who receives salvation from Jesus Christ.
